\i \cf0 \cb2 Why? Let us consider what Time means. We think of it as a neutral entity without a history of its own, a pristine backdrop against which the messy action of life takes place. But this idea is human-made and historically specific, rather than a natural and universal fact. It is most likely isolated to Indo-European cultures, amplified by the ancient Greeks and given its modern thrust by Newtonians. In short, to paraphrase Sacha Stern, 
\b the majority of cultures over history have not had a word for Time as a thing in itself
\b0 .\
