What\'92s more, as Stern reminds us, we might live more comfortably without it. Consider the anthropologist E Evans-Pritchard\'92s comparison of his own sense of Time with that of the Nuer herders he lived with in the 1930s in what is now South Sudan:\
\
"I do not think that [the Nuer] ever experience the same feeling of fighting against time or having to coordinate activities with an abstract passage of time, because their points of reference are mainly the activities themselves."\
\
The Nuer herders 
\b lived by the cattle clock
\b0 , he said, translating it into an abstract metaphor to aid his Western readers\'92 understanding. On Stereochron we have encountered something close to this in the ways the campaign secretary\'92s family judge when to harvest crops or take cattle to market.\
\

\b The cattle clock does not display Time as a succession of identical units. Rather its irregular, multiple, parallel phases are defined by the events they describe. Vestiges of this are left in our language: the blink of an eye, the shake of a lamb\'92s tale, moons ago, the crack of dawn. 
\b0 On Stereochron we have expanded those measures to changes in the sheep\'92s eye, the blooming of the evening primrose, the colour-shift of the sky, the crescendo of the dawn chorus, and the length and orientation of shadows.\
As we learnt on our Midsummer field trip, 
\b standard clock-time is not an objective model for physics any more than it is for anthropology
\b0 . In as far as we must use it for certain essential tasks on Stereochron that require accurate synchrony, let\'92s remember that the standard clock\'92s tick-tock is just another form of event against which to measure other events, as Stern points out.\
